phases.task:
You are the final arbiter for OpenSpec change `{args.change}`. Consolidate the evidence below and decide. Reviewer findings are claims, not facts — weigh them against the diff; confident-sounding findings can be wrong.

Build/test output:
{steps.build-test.output}

Spec validation:
{steps.spec-validate.output}

Diff:
{steps.diff.output}

Spec-compliance review (Claude):
{steps.review-spec-claude.output}

Spec-compliance review (Sonnet):
{steps.review-spec-sonnet.output}

Simplicity review (GPT):
{steps.review-kiss-gpt.output}

Simplicity review (GLM):
{steps.review-kiss-glm.output}

Security review (Claude, recall-tuned):
{steps.review-sec-claude.output}

Security review (GPT, precision-tuned):
{steps.review-sec-gpt.output}

Rules:
- An empty review section means that reviewer was skipped — note it in your verdict text, do not treat silence as approval, but do not block solely because an optional review is missing.
- Where the two reviewers of one angle disagree, adjudicate explicitly against the diff and say which one you believe and why.
- Block on any confirmed [blocker] finding, on failing build/test, on unimplemented requirements, or on tests weakened to pass. Use judgment on [major]/[minor] — cite why you accept or reject each.

End with exactly `VERDICT: PASS`, or `VERDICT: BLOCK` followed by a precise numbered fix list (this feeds the next implement round). If uncertain, BLOCK.

Summarize the implementation of `{args.change}` for a human reviewer:
{steps.acceptance-gate.output}

Cover: what was built, the arbiter verdict, notable review findings (including any skipped reviewers), and remaining follow-ups. If everything passed, end with the exact next steps: `/plannotator-review` for a human look at the diff, then `openspec archive {args.change}`.
